<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Retailers pressed on warranties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM LEWIS, NEIL BUCKLEY and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Electrical goods retailers ought to implement Office of Fair Trading
recommendations on the sale of extended warranties before Christmas, Mr
Nigel Griffiths, Labour's consumer affairs spokesman, said yesterday.
The OFT report, published yesterday, criticised techniques used by many
retailers to sell warranties and the wide disparity between the prices of
warranties on the same goods.
Extended warranties are insurance policies providing extra protection
against product breakdown after standard manufacturers' guarantees expire.
More than 5m warranties are sold every year in a market worth Pounds 400m.
The report called for retailers such as Dixons and Comet to provide
customers with information on the prices and conditions of extended
warranties - including those offered by manufacturers.
Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of fair trading, said he would soon
examine the setting up of a code of practice to regulate warranty sales.
Mr Griffiths said: 'Millions of electrical goods will be bought in the week
before Christmas, and I want to see retailers taking action now to ensure
that the mis-selling stops.'
Sir Bryan said he would consider a Monopolies and Mergers Commission
reference if retailers failed to implement the OFT's recommendations
'without delay'. He was looking for 'early moves towards the provision of
full point of sale information'.
He said he would expect retailers' profit margins on extended warranties to
fall more in line with margins on product sales. City analysts believe
warranties account for a large part of many electrical retailers' pre-tax
profits.
The report highlighted the wide price discrepancies between warranty
policies offered by different retailers and manufacturers for the same
products (see table).
Dixons, the UK's biggest electrical retailer, said its sales practices
already reflected most of the OFT's recommendations. Since the OFT started
its investigation, Dixons has introduced in stores leaflets carrying
comprehensive price lists of its warranties.
Kingfisher, owner of Comet, the second-biggest UK electrical retailer, said
it was introducing a computer system in stores to provide information on
both product and extended warranty prices.
Extended Warranties on Electrical Goods - A Report by the OFT. PO Box 2,
Central Way, Feltham TW14 0TG. 081 398 3405.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
PRICES OF FIVE-YEAR EXTENDED WARRANTIES
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Retailers (Insurance company)            Colour TV       Washer/dryer
                                     Sony KVX 2572     Hotpoint WD22*
                                            Pounds             Pounds
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
