<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Bitter dispute over name may end in change: Shareholders
attacked as spiteful
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Saatchi &amp; Saatchi, the holding company, now looks set to join most of the
world's top marketing services groups, including WPP, Interpublic and
Omnicom, in differentiating itself by name from its main advertising
network.
To outsiders, the fuss over names may seem ludicrously overblown, but in the
advertising world there seem to be few issues more important than whose name
goes above the door - hence the unpronounceable string of names and initials
that adorn the letterheadings of many agencies.
The question of names is inextricably linked to egos and status and Mr
Maurice Saatchi has long made clear, not least during this week's boardroom
battles, that any proposal to change the name was one of the issues on which
he was prepared to resign.
Before matters came to a head, one rival agency chief said he thought the
battle over the name had all been part of the drive to humiliate Mr Saatchi.
'I think they're just being vindictive and trying to put Maurice in his
place. It's spiteful. I think it's come to a sorry pass when a group of
shareholders can decide what your company is called without offering any
reasonable explanation for a change,' he said.
But there do also seem to be strong practical arguments for distinguishing
the holding company from its operating agencies. As the head of a rival
network said: 'In good times it probably doesn't matter. But in bad, the
sins of the holding company are visited on the sons of the group.'
For clients and staff of Saatchi &amp; Saatchi, the advertising agency, it can
have done nothing for business or morale to have been constantly linked by
name to the misfortunes and antics at Saatchi &amp; Saatchi plc.
Another argument is that it is difficult for the non-Saatchi networks in the
group to build their own 'brand' if they are constantly referred to as
Saatchi-owned companies. This is said to have been a particular hindrance to
the Bates agencies.
Also, where a group stretches beyond pure advertising and into marketing
services more generally - as is certainly the case with Saatchi &amp; Saatchi -
it gives a clearer message to clients if a non-advertising agency name is
chosen for the holding company.
</TEXT>
