<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Britain heads for fresh clash on Hong Kong
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MONTAGNON, Asia Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Britain and China were heading for another bruising row over Hong Kong last
night after three days of talks in London failed to produce a consensus on
the establishment of the territory's court of final appeal.
Mr Hugh Davies, head of the British delegation, said the colonial government
would nonetheless proceed early in the new year with legislation to
establish the court, which is to be Hong Kong's supreme judicial authority
after it reverts to China in 1997.
Mr Zhao Jihua, his Chinese counterpart, warned that the UK should not take
unilateral actions before agreement had been reached on the details of the
legislation.
Tabling of the legislation by the British side seems set to bring the matter
to a head in a way reminiscent of the decision by Hong Kong Governor Chris
Patten to proceed with his electoral reform proposed in 1992.
Britain has argued that it needs to establish the court in time to provide
legal continuity for Hong Kong after 1997, but there have been suspicions
that China is prevaricating because it would prefer not to be saddled with
arrangements in which Britain has had a hand.
Mr Zhao declined yesterday to give specific reasons for China's reluctance
to endorse the bill setting up the court. China and Britain had agreed in
principle as long ago as 1991 the basis on which the court should be set up,
he said.
But he told a meeting of the joint liaison group set up by the two countries
to administer handover arrangements that China had only recently been given
the text of the bill and needed more time for discussion.
'Pending a consensus reached by the two sides through discussion, no
unilateral action should be taken by the British side,' he said.
The proposed arrangements for the court of final appeal are controversial in
Hong Kong because the bill provides for one judge to be appointed from
overseas. While China is apparently reluctant to be tied down specifically
in this way, some liberal politicians are reluctant to accept wording that
seems to limit foreign participation to one judge.
British officials believe that putting the bill before the Legislative
Council will force the issue, because the council would only vote for a bill
providing for the participation of a single foreign judge if it was clear
that China would accept the result after 1997.
This week's meeting did reach agreement on a series of issues ranging from
Hong Kong's continuing participation in international agreements on
intellectual property and on the signing of a bilateral air agreement with
Germany.
But it was clear after the talks closed that a wide gulf remains on a number
of important issues. Mr Davies said no progress had been made on the dispute
over the colony's ninth container terminal, for which China refused to
sanction contracts.
'I urged the Chinese side to lift what is in effect a veto on the project
and pointed out once again the damage which this continuing delay is
inflicting on the economy of Hong Kong and on investor confidence more
widely.'
There was also no progress on the question of travel documents and rules on
right of abode after 1997, an important area where 'time is rapidly running
out', he said.
For its part the Chinese side complained about Hong Kong's plan to set up a
reserve fund for civil service pensions and - in an apparent reference to
relaxation of the laws on film censorship - about unilateral changes to
existing legislation which Mr Zhao said was out of line with the original
agreement on the handover.
China was also 'gravely concerned' about the recent release into the Hong
Kong community of 125 Vietnamese boat people. China wanted the question of
Vietnamese refugees dealt with before 1997, he said.
Despite the disagreements, Mr Davies said he would not characterise the
meeting as a failure and added that agreement had been reached to step its
work and hold more expert consultations.
'But I am afraid that the result does not match up to what is required and
expected of us,' he said.
'It is clear that we are going to have to do much better in the next two and
a half years if we are to live up to what people rightly expect.'
</TEXT>
