<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Reforms fail to cut the cost of bribing voters: Japan's long
and dishonourable tradition of 'money politics', thought to have been
banished by voter disgust and political change, may be reviving
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GERARD BAKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Hiroshi Mitsuzuka, the leader of one of the smaller factions in Japan's
Liberal Democratic Party, threw a party for several thousand of his closest
friends. The ostensible purpose was to celebrate the publication of his
book. Nothing was left to chance in ensuring the gathering's success, though
 -former ministers in the faction were each encouraged to sell 1,000 tickets
at Y30,000 (Pounds 190) to their wealthier supporters, and even first year
members of parliament were expected to palm off 200 tickets.
But there was, of course, an ulterior motive - fund-raising for the faction.
When the last book had been signed a total of Y135m had rolled in, less than
had been hoped for, but a useful addition to the group's coffers.
The event was just one of a sudden rush of fund-raisers in the last month.
After a long lull in parties' revenue-raising efforts, the political cash
registers have been ringing again. The demand for funds is considerable -
next year will see a rolling programme of elections in japan - local
elections in the spring, followed by national upper house elections in
summer, and throughout, the threat of a general election at any time.
But the recent round of political money-spinning events has raised fears
that Japan's long and dishonourable tradition of 'money politics', thought
to have been banished by voter disgust and political reform, may in fact be
enjoying a revival.
A succession of revelations of corruption in the last 20 years hardened the
cynicism of the Japanese towards their political bosses - from the Lockheed
affair in the 1970s to the Recruit affair of the 1980s and recent
construction-related scandals. But while these were the most lurid of the
cases of corruption, what came to trouble the Japanese more was the fact
that a myriad of unpublicised cases testified to the fact that the entire
political system ran on money.
But all that was supposed to have been ended by the voter backlash last year
that swept the LDP out of office for the first time in nearly 40 years. The
political articulation of the popular disgust was the reform package
instigated a year ago and passed into law last month, with the backing even
of a chastened LDP. These reforms come into effect on Christmas Day, but
there are widespread doubts about precisely what effect they will have in
ridding the country of 'money politics'.
The problem cannot simply be ascribed to the venality of politicians. Like
everything else in Japan, politics is an expensive business. In order to get
elected politicans have to spend vast sums of money on a pliant electorate.
For decades the unchallenged dominance of the LDP meant that political
competition was based not on ideological lines but on pecuniary ones - who
could spend the most money to buy the most votes.
The reforms were supposed to have taken away both the cause and the effect
of this demand for political 'hot' money. Japan's system of multi-member
constituencies was identified as the cause. Because more than one politican
from the same party could run against each other, the election often became
a race between war chests. The politican who could spend more lavishly on
the voters would be the winner. Replacing that with predominantly
single-member constituencies means only one candidate from each party can
run, so, the theory goes, the election turns not on money but on ideological
and policy differences.
Cynics always regarded the likely benefits of the new system as doubtful.
The progress of Japanese politics in the last six months makes it highly
unlikely that the system will change substantially. The nominal coalition
government of socialist and Liberal Democrats is in fact dominated by LDP
members and policy and it will be the principal governing party in the next
election, faced by an assortment of forces under the banner of New Frontier
Party. What these opposition parties have in common is that they were mostly
once parts of the LDP.
'The idea that there is an ideological divide in Japanese politics is even
more far-fetched now than it was in the past,' says Mr Rei Shiratori, head
of the Japan Institute for Political Studies. 'The next election will be
fought essentially between the current LDP and an opposition made up of
former LDP members. 'That means the differences will again be marginal and
will come down to who spends the most.'
And the battle is actually set to become more expensive. The reform cuts the
number of individual constituencies by half, replacing them with members
elected from a national list. So there are now fewer constituencies. 'That
means the number of votes required to win an individual seat has risen
sharply,' says Mr Dan Harada, a political consultant, 'So even more money
will have to spent on bribing the voters.'
But, argue the supporters of reform, that ignores another change that will
reduce political donations. But here too there is scepticism. Though the new
law envisages a phasing out of contributions to indivdual politicans within
five years, politicans are starting to get around the prohibition by simply
shifting their funding vehicle from themselves to their branch party. The
law does not forbid such donations. 'In effect, politicans will go on
receiving money, but in the name of their loacal party,' says Mr Shiratori.
This may be too cynical a view. One pro-reform member of parliament says:
'Last year the voters voted for real change. If they don't get it they will
punish the politicians again.'
That blithe view will be tested in the next year by the arrival of the new
system at Christmas. The voters will get a chance to express their distaste
again for the past political order. But for the time being, as the LDP holds
firmly onto the reins of power, the book launch spree seems likely to run
and run.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8651 Political Organizations.
</IN>
<XX>
