<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Japan's trade surplus up 15.5%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Japan's trade surplus jumped 15.5 per cent from a year earlier in November
to Dollars 8.55bn, but officials and economists said yesterday they still
foresaw a slow decline next year. Strong exports to recovering economies in
the US and Europe caused the surplus to rise for the first time since July
this year. Exports as a whole climbed 21.1 per cent from a year earlier to
Dollars 34.42bn. The politically sensitive surplus with the US, Japan's
biggest trading partner, expanded to Dollars 5.17bn from Dollars 4.29bn. But
a Ministry of Finance official told reporters: 'The trade surplus is still
in a shrinking trend despite November's rise.' He noted that imports
continued growing at a double-digit pace, up 23.1 per cent to Dollars
25.86bn.
