FT  17 DEC 94 / Aid and warning for Kenya
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
International aid donors yesterday signalled that they would cover Kenya's
estimated external financing gap of Dollars 800m next year, but warned the
Nairobi government to take steps to prevent public funds being misused
again.
At the end of a two-day meeting chaired by the World Bank, donors said they
'warmly welcomed' the government's public disclosure of the misappropriation
of public funds and its action this week in charging a former permanent
secretary of the treasury with conspiracy to steal. The legal action was
clearly timed to influence the Paris meeting, where, however, donors
stressed the 'critical importance' of preventing such misuse occurring
again.
Kenya was complimented by aid donors on its success over the past year in
reducing inflation to single digits, boosting growth this year to 3.3 per
cent, increasing external reserves and abolishing virtually all foreign
exchange and internal price controls.
