<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / New trade barriers in Sweden
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Sweden, which has taken steps to liberalise trade over the past four years,
will raise trade barriers again when it joins the European Union next month,
according to the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. A Gatt report
published yesterday on Sweden's trade policies and practices said prices of
imports from non-EU nations are 'in many cases' expected to rise from
January because of 'generally higher' EU tariffs and more complicated trade
control systems.
With the reintroduction of textiles and clothing quotas under the
Multi-Fibre Arrangement and other trade controls, Gatt predicts that the
number of import licence applications in Sweden could rise from a few
thousand to over 60,000 a year.
