<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Threat of rebellion over Chechnya mission: Popular protests
are demoralising the invading forces
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE LEVINE and JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
General Ivan Babichev, a senior divisional commander of the Russian force
attacking Chechnya, declared war yesterday - against his political
superiors. Addressing several hundred Chechens in the village of Novo
Shurvoi, he said: 'Any order to attack Grozny is a criminal one. This
operation contradicts the constitution. It is forbidden to use the army
against peaceful civilians. It is forbidden to shoot at the people.'
His extraordinary statement, made close to where his column has been halted
for the past three days 35 miles from the Chechen capital Grozny, is the
clearest sign yet that a significant part of the army will not fight
Chechens - in spite of overwhelming superiority on the Russian side.
Although resistance to the Russian invaders on the part of both Chechens and
their neighbours in Ingushetia has been spirited, it has been the popular
demonstrations, particularly by the women, which have halted Gen Babichev
and which are demoralising the army.
'When I look into the faces of these old women,' the general said yesterday,
'it is as if I see the face of my own mother'.
Gen Babichev has had his fill of women. They clambered over his tanks and
armoured personnel carriers in Ingushetia; they have wailed and shouted by
the side of the road; and where he has halted they have formed barriers,
dancing in the middle of the highway with their men behind them. They are a
human shield.
On the northern front, where the main fighting has occurred but where there
was only sporadic shelling yesterday, a young Chechen soldier said the
elders of the local community had gone to the Russians to appeal to them not
to fight. 'They came back and told us none of them wanted to fight, they
wanted to go home.'
A harsher message came from Mr Musa Israelov, 42, commander of the frontline
tank post on the northern perimeter near Tolstoi Yurt, where the Russian
division is now positioned. With the muzzles of Russian tanks on the hills
behind him, he said: 'If Russian parents don't take their sons back, they
will come back as corpses in buses'.
The Islamic undercurrent in the struggle has become more apparent. The
Russian nightmare of a jihad on its territory - an eventuality they tried to
prevent by taking over the border defences of Tajikistan and pouring troops
in to bolster fighting with the Afghani mujahideen - now seems a distinct
reality.
Mr Mayerbek Bokhacheev, a 28-year old fighter wearing the inscription 'Allah
Akbar' (God is Great) on his vest, said: 'This is a holy war. You can tell
Yeltsin the Islamic people of Chechnya will never retreat. Our country has
never been conquered by anyone.'
The relative calm yesterday in Grozny was observed by the Russians in the
west by clearing up the debris of smashed and burnt vehicles along the
highway, resulting from attacks over the last four days. On the northern
front, more barricades were going up; cement blocks were being moved into
place, gun emplacements strengthened and camouflage netting placed over
them.
There is now a lull in the storm. Grozny's streets are filling with people
and the impoverished market is doing more business. But the city is still
readying itself for war.
</TEXT>
