<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Arts: A 'Loose Ends' for eggheads - Radio
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN HOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Something should be done about Melvyn Bragg, if not to him. The rumour is
that a producer's diktat went out to the effect that he must be more
abrasive: if it was the producer who supports Arsenal, as revealed on
Monday's Start the Week, it merely confirms one's opinion of her judgment.
From a civilised arbiter of argument, coaxing the best from his guests,
Bragg has become a bully, slapping down those he disagrees with and giving
short shrift to those he considers, not always rightly, to be fools. It is a
little like Brian Hayes in his old LBC days, but without the sense of craggy
integrity.
There is something innately plush about Melv. He is too comfortable with
himself, which makes the discomfort he inflicts on others unacceptable; less
a rigorous crusade for truth than mandarin contempt for inferiors. And while
Hayes' victims rang in, choosing confrontation, the guests on STW have
presumably been invited because they have something to say. I would hate to
think they were being set up.
On Monday, initial boredom at the prospect of a newspaper journalist telling
us why she had given her television away was replaced by outraged sympathy
as she was verbally jostled by the assembled company of the media-wise,
seldom permitted to make her points in full, and assailed by such
intellectual attacks as Melv's dismissive assertion that all the people he
knows who say they hate television are very stupid people. So there. Melv is
of course a TV magnate, a well-known screen personality and rich with it. No
one could call him stupid.
Far from dispelling the air of self-congratulation that is turning STW into
a Loose Ends for eggheads, Melv's acerbity accentuates it in some of his
guests. PJ O'Rourke was a disappointment after his writing, the breezy
bonhomme that one dreads getting cornered by at parties, rolling along on
autopilot chuckling facetiousness and woolly generalisations.
But it has been a depressing week for the communicating classes. Mediumwave
chatted to the British brat-pack of directors who, despite the death of our
native film industry, are doing well in Hollywood. Little Action Men, every
one, saying things like 'I want to be very, very rich', not wanting to make
films appealing to a minority and boasting of being the first video (ie not
lettered) generation - well, why not if that's where the future lies? But
what became of art? At least Melv is keen on that.
Struggles to communicate have recurred in the Radio 3 programmes on the
distaff and the stave, Pride and Prejudice - a Celebration of Women
Composers. They almost qualify, as a class, for Radio 4's Scapegoats.
Tuesday's programme featured music and words from Judith Weir, restrained,
ironic and articulate on the double handicap of being a serious composer and
a woman.
Some fascinating sounds, many new to me, from composers mitteleuropaisch and
points north. But arguing about whether women's music is intrinsically
different from men's strikes me as on a par with extracting sunbeams from
cucumbers.
We all know that the sexes both bang the big drum these post-Glennie days.
It would be interesting to compare the sexes' percussion styles, a thought
prompted by Radio 3's artist of the week. James Blades started in cinemas
and circuses and ended as a favourite of Benjamin Britten.
Besides showpieces, the week's well-chosen snippets included that ominous
passage in The Turn of the Screw where the governess muses about her new job
and a frantic throbbing underlines her nervousness, tightening the suspense
unbearably.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
