<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Arts: Midnight after a hard day in the House - Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The BBC Director-General, John Birt himself, is said to the be the man
responsible for the launch of The Midnight Hour, a late-night BBC2 studio
discussion designed to 'review the parliamentary day'. It could be a smart
move. The BBC already boasts of 'setting the agenda' in the morning with the
Today programme on Radio 4 which goes out at just about the only time when
politicians, top executives and other 'opinion formers' are available to
listen. Midnight is often the only time that such people manage to see a bit
of television, so if The Midnight Hour catches on the BBC will be able to
claim that they are the gatekeepers at both ends of the political day.
But will it catch on? Launched on the evening of the State Opening of
Parliament, it has so far had five weeks of four-day transmissions (Monday
to Thursday) and has already improved considerably. For instance, the
production team seem, thank goodness, to have ditched the 'funny' song
illustrating the day's events. This idea is re-invented every time anybody
does a studio commentary series but the only times it ever worked were on
the Tonight programme in 1957 when Cy Grant sang calypsos written by Bernard
Levin, and on That Was The Week in 1962 when the scat intro was sung by the
brilliant Millicent Martin.
The producers of The Midnight Hour should now abandon their other
security-blanket devices: the fluorescent tube logo which was so trendy in
the 1980s, the cocktail bar mini-set guaranteed to make any politician look
as though he is about to do a high-stool Dicky Valentine number, and the
barmy inlay of a giant tropical fish tank which would hardly pass muster on
a yoof series. No image on television is more powerful than a talking head
against a black background and that is what they should stick to. Even the
gimmick of making the men take off their jackets can be safely dropped; we
know within two minutes whether we are watching a genuinely relaxed
conversation or a tense and contrived interview.
This depends largely on the skills of the chairman who should, ideally, have
been Vincent Hanna. At Newsnight, A Week In Politics and most recently on
Channel 4's Midnight Specials, Hanna has developed a technique combining
amiable conspiracy and rib-nudging ridicule which is admirably productive
with most politicians. He also has a phenomenal memory for political
minutiae.
However, The Midnight Hour has gone for a different chairman on each of the
four nights, the best of them being former Sunday Times editor Andrew Neil,
and Trevor Phillips, who has done outstanding work as producer and presenter
with London Weekend TV. Both are political journalists with considerable
broadcasting experience, and although Neil's instincts are those of a
political commentator, the squibs he tosses from the chair land pretty well
equally in all parts of the political spectrum.
The same cannot be said of Bernard Ingham who looks and sounds like a
survivor from a different age, but, worse, seems too often incapable of
setting aside his political allegiance. Most tedious of all, he likes to
remind us of his old glory days.
Sarah Baxter may one day fill positions of this sort splendidly, but at
present she lacks those attributes of a rugby forward which are necessary in
these circumstances. It is not a simple question of masculinity - the
decidedly feminine Betty Boothroyd has it, as she proved on the night of the
dramatic VAT vote when she bawled out MPs for crowding in over the bar of
the House and thundered 'I don't give a  - I don't care where you sit, but
you must sit down'. And they did.
The Midnight Hour has proved that it can attract cabinet ministers and their
shadows, camera pleasers such as Tony Banks, and respected war horses such
as Peter Shore. The atmosphere is beginning to feel right, and if they can
establish the idea that this is the place to let your hair down after a hard
day in the House (a few indiscreet leaks would be handy) this could well
become a long term fixture. It is the most interesting post-midnight series
for years.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVI
