<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Books: Human kind richly defined - Poetry / Douglas Dunn
reviews the latest crop of contemporary verse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DOUGLAS DUNN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Thirty-odd years ago - if you are old enough - did you ever think you would
read a poem by Allen Ginsberg, beginning 'as I cross my kitchen floor the
thought of Death returns'? I bet you didn't. Did you foretell that in his
penitent old age the arch-Beat would write an anti-smoking song? Or that he
would write poems in which he asked how he got himself into this mess, 'this
workaholic show-biz meditation market'? Is this what the Beats come to -
remorse and contrition? Lucky Kerouac, to have died before his talent and
success drove him to give up fags and booze. Ginsberg's recent poetry
(Cosmopolitan Greetings, Penguin, Pounds 7.99) subtracts from his prestige
as an icon of rhapsody and excess.
While a lot of contemporary poetry would benefit from even a few ounces of
Ginsberg's earlier fire and energy, that could not be said of Douglas
Oliver's Penniless Poetics (Bloodaxe Books, Pounds 7.95). For about 50 pages
Oliver drives on with a big, baggy stanza which is a handy instrument in a
poem of sustained narrative rollick and invention. What the poem says might
be a bit hard to take at times, which could be the same as saying that
living up to its brilliant first line - 'all politics the same crux: to
define human kind richly' - is too much a matter of the reader's conviction
and not the author's.
Oliver's poem is up-tempo and generously inventive, and much the same has to
be said for Iain Crichton Smith's poetry. His range includes almost
everything between footnotes and the 'marvellous spendthrift universe'. He
is not as sexily post-modernist, though, and much of his power stems from
short passages and even individual phrases. His poetry aspires to a timeless
lyricism:
'The moon shone like a round shield/ In a window between two countries/ Like
ice that has grown over unowned land.'
More than many poets, Smith seems to write straight from dreams, which might
be why his work carries a look of spontaneity. Ends &amp; Beginnings (Carcanet
Press, Pounds 8.95) shows a poet now in his 60s writing as if with a new
lease of life. It includes some of his best work.
A more exact, engraved rather than brushed poetry, confirms just what an
interesting poet Pauline Stainer is (The Ice-Pilot Speaks, Bloodaxe Books,
Pounds 6.95) - as well as setting up a contrast with the immediacy of
Ginsberg and Oliver, or Crichton Smith's less disciplined lyricism. Her best
gift is an artist's discretion in coaxing what she is saying onto the page
(see, for instance, 'Between Stations' and 'A Study for the Badminton
Game').
Today's version of the courtly in poetry is a self-aware reliance on art,
music and other literature, and there is a lot of that in her work. The
originality of her perceptions prevents its deliberately 'cultural' climate
from becoming precious.
Whatever Geoff Hattersley has to worry about, it is not preciosity. Some
poems in Don't Worry (Bloodaxe Books Pounds 7.95), though, give an
impression of slightness, cleverness, or embarrassment in case there is a
danger of being too serious. There is real gusto in his work as well as a
manic but controlled humour. He can evoke odd or unnerving states of mind,
enigmas, private terrors, domestic emergencies, with techniques or ways of
looking at things that seem devised to give the familiar a good shake. 'Time
passes slowly here in south Yorkshire. The dustbinmen came yesterday . . .
My cough gets on my nerves but at least I own it.' Cheeky, imaginative,
cerebral, witty - it is poetry with a lot to say for itself.
'Poet Laureate Ritual Bath Murder' in Douglas Houston's new book, The
Hunters in the Snow (Bloodaxe Books, Pounds 6.95), is as certain a piece of
literary satire as I have come across in a while - although the object of
the satire is how Ted Hughes is mythologised by his less intelligent
admirers. Houston's characteristic poems tend to be chunkier, more serious
and sorrowful although sharpened by quirky humour and observations. A deft
technical command, confident imagery - 'Night falling like a weightless slab
of slate' - and an agreeable first person singular, make this an enjoyable
collection. Less showily formal than others, 'Encounter' and 'Taking a
Break' suggest that simplicity is the most poetic wile of all.
Poems of Gerard Woodward's such as 'After the Deafening', 'A Nocturnal
Breakfast' and 'Tomatoes' jolt with an almost disturbing originality in
After the Deafening (Chatto &amp; Windus, Pounds 7.99). 'Making Strange' is a
process at once mysterious and recognisable. You feel that you have been
shown something new, or that the previously familiar really has been
re-examined with a fresh eye and intellect.
Not all his poems work anything like as well, but when they do the result
feels like a sting to the nervous system.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
