<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Financial Planning): When charities pay -
Briefcase
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
I have been been asked to help in raising funds for the benefit of my local
church and we will be arranging a number of functions for which admission
will be charged. One event, also involving admission charges, is going to be
organised by people not connected with the church. What are the VAT
consequences?
The views of the Customs and Excise are set out in VAT leaflet 701/1/92 and
we suggest you get a copy. In any case, we suggest you take independent
professional advice before starting your fund-raising.
If a charity carries on a business, it must be registered for VAT if its
turnover exceeds the limits for registration. It could help for a charity to
be registered even if its turnover is less than the registration limit. The
potential advantage is the recovery of input tax on charges which it incurs.
One activity which is always treated as a business is charging for admission
to premises. There is, however, a VAT exemption for 'one-off' fund-raising
events. The detailed rules are set out in the leaflet.
The VAT consequences of the funds raised by the other organisation may be
more difficult to determine. If it is acting as the church's agent, then its
activities will be treated as being carried on by the church and normal VAT
rules will follow. If not, then the organisation itself will have to pay VAT
if its turnover is high enough.
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All enquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
</TEXT>
