<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / How to Spend It: Perfect gifts for difficult people - Lucia
van der Post conjures up an imaginary family to offer ideas for presents for
real relatives
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LUCIA VAN DER POST
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Families, families . . . console yourself, everybody else's are difficult,
too. But, as Tolstoy might have said, it is the difficult ones that are the
most interesting. But no matter how difficult they may seem, somewhere there
is a present to match. Here is an archetypally difficult family, and
presents to please them.
CHARLES: IN RECESSION
In the 1980s Charles' salary looked like a telephone number. But these days
life is tougher. The financial investment firm he worked for has gone under,
his losses at Lloyd's still loom and Charles spends his days helping to put
some financial order into his wife's catering business.
He does not often have to wear a suit so anything from somewhere like Racing
Green (0345-331177) would help restore his fading wardrobe or, better still,
a pair of stone-coloured cords or moleskin trousers from Hackett or Johnnie
Boden (081-964 2662). A Thomas Pink shirt would go down well, too, for those
days when he has to face the bank manager.
Now that Charles does not have to cut much of a figure in the office his
waistline has become rather slack. He would love a chin-up bar at just
Pounds 9.99 - tones up the biceps and the torso - from Lillywhites,
Piccadilly Circus, London W1.
Charles loves good things but can afford them less and less - he would be
thrilled by a finely-made Caran d'Ache pen - all slim lines with a good
strong pocket clip and a giant-sized refill for Pounds 99.50.
He badly needs cheering up so a real boys' own adventure would be just the
thing. Give him a day out learning to be a rally driver for Pounds 225.
(01608- 678339)
ZAC AND SKY: VERY, VERY GREEN
Zac and Sky are concerned about the third world, conservation,
over-population and waste. Zac is in computers and Sky is an occupational
therapist but hates it.
Sky sees herself as an earth mother but her concern about using up the
earth's resources means she only has one child. She is worried about her
Daisy sitting in front of screens all day, laying down cholesterol for her
later years.
Power Rangers In-Line skates ('the most happening way to work out') would be
good for eight-year-old Daisy. With a high ankle support, soft inner
linings, strong chassis and PVC wheels, they are just the thing and at
Pounds 19.99 a pair (from Toys 'R' Us) Daisy will find them 'awesome'.
Then Sky loves traditional games such as Triominos from Goliath Games. It
is, she has heard, the perfect family game. It encourages 'interactive play'
something Sky is very keen on. It won the Game of the Year in the
Netherlands and for just Pounds 9.99 ought to give a lot of bonding.
Daisy will certainly find an Urban Forestry Kit, Pounds 2.99 from Natural
Fact, 193 King's Road, London SW3 (mail order 071- 352 4283) in her
stocking. The kit consists of three seedlings to plant to help prevent
global warming.
Sky herself would love almost anything from Natural Fact, 192 King's Road,
London SW3 - an ecru towelling robe at Pounds 49.99 or Acca Kappa natural
straw massage slippers at Pounds 30. As for beauty products (not that Sky
uses them much) Green Things, 70 Chalk Farm Road, London NW1 is the place.
Sky believes in fair trade and loves anything with an 'ethnic' label. Kashi
(294/5 High Holborn, London WC1), for instance, has hand-made papier-mache
decorations, children's wooden jig-saw puzzles at Pounds 6, and
silver-plated wine glasses from Pounds 4.50, all made by extremely poor
women in India.
JANET: STRESSED SINGLE MOTHER
Janet is in her late 30s, a media person with an independent TV company and,
as if that was not stressful enough, she is a single mother to
seven-year-old Simon. She is busy, busy, busy. She never has time to shop so
what she needs are presents to soften her home and things for herself.
Give Simon a PGL Adventure holiday weekend (Pounds 79 plus insurance
0989-764211). Simon would have a ball and Janet (dearly as she loves Simon)
would love a weekend to herself. She could indulge in all those new age
therapies she is so keen on. She would love a voucher for aromatherapy
(Aromatherapy Associates 071-731 8129, Pounds 38 a session) and she is
always worried that she never has time to pretty up the house so fresh
flowers arriving regularly would do wonders for her morale. For roughly
Pounds 150 Parterre (071-323 1623) would send a bunch of seasonal flowers
once a month for six months (delivery charges vary but in the London area
would be about Pounds 3).
Jewellery, if you get it right, is always a good present. A multi-stranded
pearl choker from Coleman Douglas Pearls, 97b Drayton Gardens, London SW10
(starting prices Pounds 380) or one of their huge pearl cuffs (from Pounds
480) would be wonderful. She has also had her eye on Sandra Cronan's
collection of faux jewellery at 18 Burlington Arcade, London W1 - in
particular her aquamarine collet necklace at Pounds 850.
Janet likes glam clothes - she is, after all in a visual business - so
anything from Browns, South Molton Street, London W1 would be appreciated.
She hankers for Mulberry's Chenille coat at Pounds 495 or a delicate devore
scarf by Camilla Ridley (small ones are Pounds 99 but the luscious
shawl-sized ones are Pounds 249 . . . find them at Harrods, Liberty's, Space
NK).
HENRY AND ROSE: NEED SPOILING
Rose, dear Rose, has spent the last 20 years looking after the four
children, tending the house, doing the flowers in the church on Sunday while
Henry has been tending his patients as a country GP. They are both
unaccustomed to spending on themselves - what with four lots of school fees
and their youngest son's surprising academic success (what was his Ph. D all
about? They never did quite get a handle on it) required years of parental
support, and then the grandchildren coming along, the Old Manor House is
looking a bit shabby . . . as are their wardrobes.
So Henry and Rose are easy . . . spoiling is what they need. Rose would love
a black cashmere tunic sweater which can be given a demure elegance by the
addition of heavy ivory silk detachable collars and cuffs (Pounds 265 from
Madeleine Hamilton, Chichester Rents, Chancery Lane, London WC2A 1EG and 94
Richmond Avenue, Islington, London N1 0LU. Mail order 071-833 3388). Or she
would love a heavy matt silk shirt with double cuffs (Pounds 75 from TM
Lewin, 103-106 Jermyn Street, London W1).
These days Rose has difficulty keeping track of her spectacles - so her
grandchildren might give her some pretty haematite beaded spectacle ropes to
hang them around her neck. At Pounds 19.99 a time (including p+p ) from
Crystal Eyes, 12 Bemish Road, London SW15 1DG (081-789 3528). If Henry is
feeling rich he could give her one of the beautiful antique lorgnettes or
opera glasses sold by Optika on the Lower Ground Floor at Harrods (not cheap
 -anything from Pounds 250 upwards - but very special).
As a girl Rose was a promising artist and now at last she has time to start
doing water-colours again - she would love the drawing pad holder,
beautifully encased in leather, by Papyrus (Pounds 97.50, 48 Fulham Road,
London SW3 6HH, 071- 584 8022) and if somebody is feeling generous there is
a paint brush tube with a waterproof lining that fits on to it with a strap
for Pounds 97.50.
Rose likes jewellery. Caroline Charles, 56/57 Beauchamp Place, London SW3
(071-225 3197) is her sort of shop and this winter it has marvellous
antique-looking diamante chokers and earrings as well as some dashing
leopard skin gloves which would wake up the sidesmen in the local church on
a Sunday morning.
Henry has seen too many of his patients slide into an unhealthy late middle
age so he is making determined efforts to take his shape in hand. A
precision-made marching compass with a luminous dial and a magnifying sight
lens at Pounds 14.95 (from Presents for Men, 01295-750100) would lend his
walks some interest. So, too, would a pedometer which clips to the waistband
and measures the distance covered, approximate number of steps taken and
calories consumed. By Sportsline at Lillywhites, Piccadilly Circus, London
W1, Pounds 19.99.
Henry loves single malt whisky or, at the end of one of Rose's splendid
diners, some cognac (get him an XO Cognac at Pounds 90). A classic from
Talking Books for when he is driving round the countryside would go down
well (make sure it is unabridged for Henry knows his classics), as would
some very fine tea.
NIGEL: DASHING IN ADVERTISING
Nigel is in his early 30s and really rather dashing (though not quite as
dashing as he would like to be). Much to the bewilderment of his masters at
school who remember him as rather lightweight Nigel is doing very well in
advertising.
Though Nigel has had a mobile for some time he is rather bored with the
bulge it makes in his Paul Smith suits - he would love the little Sony
('smaller than a pack of playing cards,' he read somewhere) mobile. He knows
it is expensive (anywhere between Pounds 200 and Pounds 400 depending on the
discounts) but it would be just the thing.
In the 1980s his bathroom was full of premium-priced lotions and potions but
now he is wary of glitzy names selling what he refers to as 'coloured water'
and goes for classic lines which he likes to think of as 'his': Chanel's
'Pour Monsieur', Givenchy's 'Gentlemen' or anything by Geo. F. Trumper are
the classics he likes.
In the 1980s he would spend hours watching American football but 1990s man
supports his local soccer team. So he would love a video of his favourite
club (Arsenal, Spurs, Chelsea . . . they are all doing them). He has
intellectual pretensions so a video of a French classic movie would please
him.
Nigel eats out rather less than once he did and is into cooking - lots of
pasta which satisfies his need to feel creative without taxing it too
severely. A proper Parmesan grater would go down well (Pounds 12.75), as
would a terracotta egg-tray for Pounds 6.75 and an espresso maker that goes
on top of the cooker with a ceramic pot on top around Pounds 20 or sweet
little aluminium knives at Pounds 3.95 to Pounds 4.95, just right for
spreading tapenade on his crostini. All from The Conran Shop, Michelin
House, Fulham Road, London SW3.
He is, of course, highly computer literate and would not move without his
laptop. But he is the first to admit that computers are not things of great
beauty. Mulberry understands him perfectly and has produced a laptop
computer case in brandy harness-leather with solid brass fittings which
would be just the job for Pounds 395.
SOPHIE: DADDY'S GIRL
Sophie has just turned 19 and is not what you might call academic. Her
A-levels, much to Daddy's displeasure were not up to much, so after her
secretarial course she took a nice little job in an art gallery. The salary
is poor but she likes the slight whiff of bohemian glamour attached to it
(after all Lady Helen Windsor did all right, didn't she?) and they do not
mind if your lunch-hours drift on a bit.
She would really like anything from Nicole Farhi (Chanel is, dare we say it,
just a little passe this Christmas) or APC (130 Draycott Avenue, London SW3)
and what she would like in particular is a silver tunic or leather-wrap
mini-skirt. Then she has her eye on an absolutely plain polo-neck wool body
from Donna Karan's DKNY range at Pounds 79, any accessory by Patrick Cox (8
Symons Street, London SW3).
She longs to own a Discman (about Pounds 200). Now that she has to be
tolerably organised for work she would like a black patent Bill Amberg
rucksack to hold her personal belongings (Pounds 70 from Harvey Nichols but
there is an excellent cheaper version at Debenhams for Pounds 35).
She has always longed for a silver jig-saw ring Pounds 144 from Georg
Jensen, 15 New Bond Street, London W1 or silver pen from Tiffany which would
fit into her Filofax (Pounds 34).
</TEXT>
