<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Markets): Witches lurk behind the Christmas
tree - Wall Street - As the Dow bubbles unexpectedly, Patrick Harverson
predicts trouble ahead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The only predictable feature of the stock market this year has been its
unpredictability. A little more than a week ago, Wall Street was reeling
from a 50-point loss on the Dow Jones Industrial Average. It was the latest
in a string of big sell-offs which had dragged blue-chip stocks close to
their lows of the year and sucked much of the confidence out of the market.
At the time, investors - already bruised by rising interest rates and fears
of a darkening economic outlook - were also being battered by the biggest
municipal bankruptcy in US history and the mysterious cancellation of a
Dollars 2bn cash distribution by the nation's biggest mutual fund. The
climate on Wall Street was so chilly that most pundits predicted that the
market would miss its traditional year-end rise in share prices - the
so-called 'December rally'.
This week, however, the mood abruptly changed, and like many of the market's
moves this year, initially no one was quite sure what was behind the shift.
Since its big decline on December 8, the Dow has rebounded more than 90
points, or 2.5 per cent. Now, talk of a December rally is being revived, and
investors are realising that there may be something under the Christmas tree
for them, after all.
The market's turnaround can be traced to the easing of fears that the
Federal Reserve would raise interest rates once more before the year ended.
The selling of shares in early December followed a strong November
employment report which led some analysts to predict that the Fed would
tighten monetary policy for the seventh, and final, time this year after the
December 20 meeting of its open market committee.
To this grim prospect of yet another rate increase was added the bankruptcy
of Orange County, California, and the cancelled payout at the Fidelity
Group's Magellan Fund. Although neither story had direct implications for
share prices (the Orange county debacle only briefly roiled the bond market
after it sparked a fire sale of billions of dollars in government agency
securities, and the Magellan mix-up subsequently proved to be the product of
a mathematical mistake), they clearly undercut sentiment.
In the past week, however, a string of economic data has forced analysts to
reconsider their predictions of a December 20 interest rate increase. The
most important statistics concerned inflation. On Tuesday and Wednesday the
government reported that producer prices rose by 0.5 per cent and consumer
prices rose by 0.3 per cent in November. Neither figure was encouraging, but
in both cases the closely-watched 'core' measure of price inflation (which
excludes volatile components which distort the indices) rose at a slower
rate than expected. The market was also encouraged by a report from the
Philadelphia Fed which showed signs of moderate growth in business activity
and only mild inflationary pressures in the region.
Taken together, the data comforted investors who had been worried about
another tightening of monetary policy. Ironically, the Orange County
bankruptcy may also have contributed to the easing of investors' fears,
because another rise in interest rates would have further undermined the
value of Orange County's troubled bond and derivatives portfolio.
Stocks were also aided this week by fresh declines in bond yields. In the
past eight days the yield on the 30-year bond has dropped from 8 per cent to
7.85 per cent. This has helped allay concerns that rising bond yields would
lure cash out of stocks into the Treasury market. The favourable move in
bonds, however, has been offset by a sharp rise in yields on shorter-term
government securities, such as two-year notes. This divergence has led to a
further flattening in the yield curve - the graph of yields on securities
with differing maturities - and, as bond market analysts never tire of
pointing out, a rapid flattening of the yield curve typically precedes a
sharp slowdown in economic growth.
To most equity investors, however, the flattening yield curve is a technical
phenomenon of little interest, and this weekend they are likely to be
basking in the warm glow of the Dow's best weekly showing since early
October.
Yet, they should be warned against making too much of the gains of the past
five days because for most of the week trading was greatly influenced by the
manoeuvrings of institutions ahead of Friday afternoon's 'triple-witching
hour'. Triple-witching is the name given to the simultaneous expiration of
stock options and futures, which happens four times a year and often
produces exceptional short-term movements in share prices.
This week, these movements were mostly upwards, which made for some handsome
gains in the Dow. Yet, they were gains which only cloaked the market's
underlying weaknesses - without them, the Dow's advance would have been
modest. Come Monday, share prices are likely to drop initially, and the
market will almost certainly be sporting a triple-witching-sized hangover.
