<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Russian general refuses to fight Chechen rebels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD and STEVE LEVINE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GROZNY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Growing opposition among senior Russian military officers to the invasion of
Chechnya reached the front line yesterday when General Ivan Babichev,
commander of one of the three divisions sent into the breakaway republic,
refused to continue fighting.
His statement, made to a crowd of Chechen villagers, directly flouted the
orders of President Boris Yeltsin. It is the most damaging blow the Russian
administration has suffered since the Chechen crisis began, and signals a
dangerously mutinous mood within the officer corps.
In Moscow, it was reported that Mr Yeltsin would chair a meeting today of
the country's security council which would discuss the crisis and consider
what action, if any, to take against the recalcitrant general. Mr Yeltsin
has given Chechens until midnight tonight to hand over their arms or face a
military crackdown.
Gen Babichev, addressing several hundred Chechens near his division, 35
miles west of the capital Grozny, said that 'the Russian leaders can condemn
us but we are not going to shoot. We are not going to use our tanks against
the people'.
His is the westernmost of three divisions sent to Chechnya last Sunday - and
one which has appeared demoralised before the resistance it met in the
neighbouring republic of Ingushetia.
Only the northern division, reportedly joined by units of the eastern
division, has reached positions near Grozny. Chechen fighters were saying
yesterday that villagers had with some success appealed to its soldiers not
to fight.
Gen Babichev, in defying his orders, has joined calls made by the other
top-level military refuseniks - General Boris Gromov, deputy defence
minister, and General Alexander Lebed, the popular commander of the 14th
Army. This week they criticised the intervention, with Gen Lebed saying
Russia risked 'getting involved in a war with the entire Moslem world'.
However, Gen Babichev's statements are more damaging to Moscow's political
authority as they come from an officer in the field. They also give a
publicity and morale boost to the leadership of General Dzhokar Dudayev, the
Chechen president.
Mr Victor Chernomyrdin, the Russian prime minister, said yesterday he was
ready to meet Gen Dudayev. Gen Dudayev repeated his readiness for talks 'at
the highest political level'.
Though most firing had stopped in Grozny last night and the Chechen fighters
had been ordered to disengage and pull back, both sides continue to threaten
all-out war.
Threats of rebellion, Page 2
</TEXT>
