<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / World Stock Markets (Europe): Milan rises in calm before
expected storm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Markets Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Italy had its own agenda yesterday. But where equity markets were strong, as
in New York, London, and Frankfurt, they were accompanied mostly by the
expiry of futures and options contracts, writes Our Markets Staff.
MILAN took advantage of the relative political calm to move higher again,
ahead of next week's expected storm when Mr Silvio Berlusconi, the prime
minister, faces a confidence vote that could topple him from power.
The Comit index rose 13.94 or 2.4 per cent to 605.77, up 0.7 per cent on the
week, dealers reporting a further awakening of foreign demand.
The banks remained in focus. Credito Romagnolo was L537 higher at L18,884 in
response to the Cariplo's counter-bid. Credito Italiano rose L24 to L1,645
and BCI was L50 up at L3,331 amid speculation that the two might launch a
joint offer for Rolo.
Banca Nazionale dell'Agricoltura rose L265 or 10 per cent to L2,909 on
renewed speculation about a shake-up in its shareholder structure.
Telecoms were supported by ministerial approval of some concessions on
tariffs and fees charged by the state for its lines. Telecom Italia moved
ahead L121 to L3,883 and Stet L61 to L4,385.
Fiat rose L209 or 3.8 per cent to L5,707 after the company said that its
results to October 31 and forecasts for the full year were continuing to
show signs of improvement.
James Capel, which upgraded the stock to a buy this week, commented that
since July there had been a marked improvement in both the Italian car
market and Fiat's position within it. The company was also making progress
in other major European markets and was performing exceptionally well in
Latin America.
PARIS failed to build on early gains as the little momentum that was evident
during the morning petered out after lunch. The CAC-40 index slipped 6.94 to
1,924.16, a fall of 0.6 per cent on the week.
Peugeot, down FFr22 or 3 per cent at FFr725, but off a session's low of
FFr720, was hit by a big sell order in reaction to comments from the company
on Thursday that seemed to suggest that second-half results would show only
a small improvement over the first six months.
But, said Mr Christopher Will of Lehman Brothers, the picture could be quite
different; he said the group's sales have been holding up extremely well
during December, after a strong performance in November, and he believed his
full-year earnings target of FFr2.5bn, following a first-half FFr688m, was
on line.
Hoare Govett downgraded Moulinex, off 3 per cent at FFr101.30, from buy to
sell on the expectation that its earnings recovery will take longer than
expected. The electrical appliance manufacturer reported a higher half-year
loss on Thursday.
AMSTERDAM's derivatives expiry passed quietly and the AEX index rose 0.69 to
408.38, up 0.5 per cent on the week.
KPN added Fl 1.10 at Fl 57.80, bringing its gain on the week to 6.25 per
cent following the announcement that Unisource, in which the Dutch telecoms
group has a stake, is to link up with AT&amp;T, of the US.
ZURICH saw further demand for blue chips which took the SMI index 6.7 higher
to 2,604.7, for a 1.1 per cent rise on the week. The financial sector
remained focused on CS Holding and Swiss Re after Thursday's announcement of
an alliance to develop financial derivatives on reinsurance. CS Holding rose
SFr17 to SFr546, with some investors said to be switching out of Swiss Re
into the bank. Swiss Re gave up much of Thursday's advance, easing SFr7 to
SFr787.
Cyclicals remained volatile, with BBC declining SFr5 to SFr1,096, while
Sulzer lost SFr10 to SFr866. Fischer recovered after Thursday's fall with a
rise of SFr30 to SFr1,530.
Landis &amp; Gyr, still supported by Wednesday's better than expected full-year
results, put on SFr9 at SFr804.
BRUSSELS saw the Bel-20 index rise 10.61 to 1,394.44, a fraction higher on
the week, as dealers took positions at the start of the two-week trading
account. Cockerill added BFr5 at BFr205 ahead of its Bel-20 debut on Monday,
and business in Union Miniere was lifted by block trades as the shares rose
BFr50 to BFr2,510.
COPENHAGEN fell, the KFX index losing 1.17 to 91.54. Sophus Berendsen, the
holding company which owns Rentokil, of the UK, dropped DKr22 or 4.5 per
cent to DKr470 after Thursday's revelation that divestment losses in 1994,
at DKr158m, would be some DKr60m higher than expected after the sale of a US
engineering unit.
Written and edited by William Cochrane, John Pitt and Michael Morgan
