FT  17 DEC 94 / UK Company News: Tate &amp; Lyle in Pounds 36m Mexican
investment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tate &amp; Lyle, the sugar and sweeteners group, yesterday announced a Dollars
56m (Pounds 35.8m) investment in Grupo Industrial Azucarero de Occidente,
Mexico's fifth largest sugar group.
The UK company is buying a 49 per cent stake from the Saenz family, whose
trusts will continue to own the remaining majority share. The Mexican
company, also known as the Saenz Group, recorded turnover of some Pounds
89.1m for the 10 months to October 31, with pre-tax profits of Pounds 5.6m.
Net assets stood at Pounds 69.3m.
Saenz has an estimated 7 per cent of the Mexican sweetener market, which
produces approximately 4m tonnes a year. The top five sugar processors in
Mexico account for about 60 per cent of total Mexican output and 64 per cent
of refined sugar production.
Tate &amp; Lyle said that Saenz's operation of two mills in the north-eastern
state of Tamaulipas and one in Jalisco, gave quick access to the growing
markets in Guadalajara, Monterrey and northern Mexico.
It added that the investment would enable the group to play a part in the
fast expanding soft drinks market in Mexico. Strong demand was also expected
from the food processing and retail grocery markets. The move was part of
the company's strategy of expanding into emerging markets through joint
ventures and partnerships.
</TEXT>
