<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Letters to the Editor: Bringing right people to account for
malpractice
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr GUY DEHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, I fear John Mason's article ('Corporate manslaughter verdict poses
legal dilemma', December 13) on corporate manslaughter following the
conviction in the Lyme Bay canoe trial misses the point.
Months before the disaster two instructors had written to the managing
director about safety at the centre, warning that unless something was done
'you might find yourself trying to explain why someone's son or daughter
will not be coming home'.
At the trial, Mr Justice Ognall made it clear that it was the failure to
heed this warning that separated this case from any other of its kind. No
doubt it was also relevant to the managing director's jail term.
If any of the five warnings about the Herald fleet sailing with bow doors
open had been addressed to the managing director or board of P&amp;O, the case
in the Zeebrugge prosecution might well have been put to the jury. As it was
those warnings got lost in middle management. The key point, then, is with
whom a serious concern is raised, rather than merely the size of the
organisation.
The message from this case is that an effective check on serious malpractice
in the workplace is to make sure that those in charge know of it.
Increasingly responsible leaders in the public and private sectors are open
to such concerns and address them properly.
They know it is only right that, when people in their positions have actual
notice of any unwarranted dangers, they can and should expect to account for
their response.
If the law or good business provided otherwise, they would do little to
promote the doctrine of accountability in organisations or to protect the
public.
Guy Dehn,
director,
Public Concern at Work,
Lincoln's Inn House,
42 Kingsway,
London WC2B 6EN
</TEXT>
