<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Advertising flag-bearer made all seem possible: Maurice
Saatchi seen as industry mould-breaker
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Last night may have ended in humiliating defeat but there are many in the
advertising business who fervently believe Maurice Saatchi must still rate
as one of the industry's all-time greats.
With his brother Charles he built what was in its heyday the number one
advertising agency in the world. It is still probably the only advertising
'brand' that the average person - in the UK at least - could readily name.
One leading member of the advertising establishment sums it up: 'Maurice has
had an enormous influence as a flag-bearer for advertising. The chutzpah of
the brothers made it seem that anything was possible and it could all be
done from the UK. They were an enormous force for good. It's a pity it all
went wrong.'
Born 48 years ago to Iraqi Jewish parents, Maurice can be a reserved - even
remote - and bookish figure. His chief strengths are considered to be his
intellect - he is said to have taken with great ease his first-class degree
from the London School of Economics - and his charm, when he wishes to
exercise it, with clients.
While neither of the brothers likes the limelight, Maurice has been the one
to act as front man, leaving Charles to play the reclusive, volatile,
creative genius. According to a former close associate, Maurice 'had clients
eating out of his hand - he really did the job with companies like Procter &amp;
Gamble'.
But others complain that he deliberately kept himself distant from staff and
all but the most important clients. One said: 'I wouldn't say he is an
enigma, he isn't interesting enough for that. He's very grey - a bit of a Mr
Major. Charlie is much more flamboyant.'
It was Charles who was first into the business and had already established a
reputation as a creative ad-man when his brother Maurice joined him from
publishing to form Saatchi &amp; Saatchi in 1970. It was Charles' advert for the
Health Education Council, depicting a pregnant man and the slogan Would you
be more careful if it was you that got pregnant that first brought them to
wider public attention.
But it was Saatchi &amp; Saatchi's relationship with Margaret Thatcher and the
Conservative party and, in particular, the Labour isn't working poster
campaign, that turned Saatchi into a household name in the UK. Through the
1970s and 1980s the name spread across the globe as acquisitions spiralled,
taking in public relations, market research and management consultancy
businesses. The frenzy reached its peak with Saatchi's unconsummated
approaches to Midland Bank in 1987.
Maurice may have been the frontman, but close associates say it was Charles
who was the one with the drive to take on the world. One said: 'The engine
room was Charles, not Maurice. Charles was always the guy who pushed and
pushed. Maurice responded to that but was always more laid back. Maurice was
the public face but Charles was the one who had unfettered ambition.'
It was the near collapse of the company, after heavy borrowings and the
onset of recession, which led to a financial restructuring in 1991 and the
beginning of the end for Maurice, who had by then ceded the chief executive
role.
Some fellow advertising professionals feel he should have called it quits at
this point. 'Like a lot of merchant adventurers, he's been nowhere near as
effective since his wings have been clipped,' said one. 'It could be argued
that he probably should have bought his agency back and started again, or
let other people get on with it and pursued his merchant adventuring
elsewhere.'
Maurice's main role in recent years has been to open doors for new business
and keep clients - in particular Mars and British Airways - happy. But even
in this function he has had his critics. According to one former associate:
'He schmoozed at the very highest level but made a point of not meeting your
regular marketing director types who were desperate to say they had met the
brothers.'
The head of a rival group - who is highly critical of events last year when
there appeared to be a campaign to oust chief executive Charlie Scott -
nevertheless agrees that Maurice has earned his place in advertising
history.
He said: 'Maurice raised advertising in the public consciousness in a way
that nobody has ever done before. He had a sense of vision and courage that
few in our business have had. Agencies throughout the world used to sit
around waiting to be swallowed by Americans. What Maurice did was to change
those rules, probably for ever.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
