FT  17 DEC 94 / US housing starts increase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A 7 per cent increase in US housing starts between October and November,
reported yesterday, provided fresh evidence of buoyant economic growth
despite repeated efforts by the Federal Reserve to curb demand by raising
interest rates.
Fed policymakers meet again next Tuesday and could decide to raise
short-term rates by a further half point to 6 per cent. Most Wall Street
analysts, however, expect the Fed to delay its next move until the New Year
partly because of jitters in bond markets following the Orange County
bankruptcy. By late January the Fed would also be able to assess whether
unexpectedly strong consumer spending in November had carried over into the
Christmas period.
The housing figures surprised analysts, many of whom were looking for an
increase of only about 2 per cent. Forecasters generally had assumed a 5 per
cent fall in starts in October signalled a period of more sluggish home
building following increases in mortgage rates.
