FT  17 DEC 94 / Mercosur set for January 1
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OURO PRETO, BRAZIL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The four South American countries in the Mercosur trade group yesterday
settled all their differences and said they were ready for the trade area to
become a full customs union from January 1 as planned. Foreign ministers
from Brazil, Argentina, Paraguay and Uruguay reached agreement on a number
of outstanding problems after a hectic night of negotiation.
The agreements will be included in the document, to be known as the protocol
of Ouro Preto, which is to be signed by the four presidents today and will
give Mercosur a similar legal status to the European Union. The protocol
also sets out rules for the Mercosur institutions such as an arbitration
system for disputes and rules to promote competition and ease customs
procedures. The four countries agreed the final lists of products, mainly
those considered unready to face full competition, which will be allowed to
keep domestic tariffs for four more years rather than cut them to zero
immediately.
</TEXT>
