<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / UK wins carbon energy tax battle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CAROLINE SOUTHEY and HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The European Union's attempt to reach a common position on energy taxes
looked in tatters yesterday after environment ministers agreed to let member
states adopt individual approaches to plans to cut carbon dioxide emissions,
A deal reached at a meeting in Brussels on Thursday evening means that
opponents of a proposed EU-wide carbon energy tax, led by the UK, have won
their battle against the measure.
It is an embarrassing blow to the EU ahead of an international conference
next March in Berlin to consider further steps to cutting CO emissions.
The conference is the most important international gathering on the
environment since the 1992 Rio de Janeiro Earth Summit.
The EU's failure to agree is particularly difficult for the German
government, which had pushed most strongly for the carbon tax ahead of the
Berlin meeting.
Mr John Gummer, UK environment minister, said he was 'very pleased' with the
outcome, which was in line with the broader understanding on a CO tax
reached at last weekend's European Council summit in Essen.
A British official said this meant that individual countries were free to
make their own provisions for meeting emission targets and that the idea of
a European Union-wide energy tax 'was dead in the water'.
Under the Essen compromise, economic and finance ministers will draw up a
'common strategy' for reducing emissions, which could also include increases
in excise duty or extensions of duty to cover new fuels.
Although the energy tax measures will be voluntary, Commission officials
said the majority of member states would seek to apply them.
Business leaders in Europe have lobbied hard against a CO tax, arguing that
it would hurt industry's competitiveness in relation to their US and Asian
counterparts.
Opposition from the UK government has focused on national sovereignty.
Earlier this year, Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor of the exchequer, said
the government would not accept the principle of taxes imposed from
Brussels.
But the tax has found favour in some eco-conscious member states such as
Germany, Denmark and the Netherlands. Other governments support the tax as a
means of raising revenue.
The European Union is committed to stabilising CO emissions at 1990 levels
by the year 2000 under the Rio Convention on Climate Change. All 12 member
states have already agreed the targets and that more measures may be
necessary if the targets are to be met.
Ironically, the UK can afford to take a tough line on the tax as it is well
placed to meet its Rio commitments.
</TEXT>
